# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1-triacontanol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] In one industrial chemical synthesis, acetylene reacts with two equivalents of formaldehyde to form butyne-1,4-diol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Hydrogenation of butyne-1,4-diol gives butane-1,4-diol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] It is also made on an industrial scale from maleic anhydride in the Davy process, which is first converted to the methyl maleate ester, then hydrogenated.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Other routes are from butadiene, allyl acetate and succinic acid.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] A biological route to BD has been commercialized that uses a genetically modified organism.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] The biosynthesis proceeds via 4-hydroxybutyrate.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is used industrially as a solvent and in the manufacture of some types of plastics, elastic fibers and polyurethanes.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] In organic chemistry, 1,4-butanediol is used for the synthesis of γ-butyrolactone (GBL).
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] In the presence of phosphoric acid and high temperature, it dehydrates to the important solvent tetrahydrofuran.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] At about 200 °C in the presence of soluble ruthenium catalysts, the diol undergoes dehydrogenation to form butyrolactone.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] It is used to synthesize 1,4-butanediol diglycidyl ether which is then used as a reactive diluent for epoxy resins.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] 1,4-Butanediol is used in the production of polybutylene terephthalate (PBT) plastic.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] World production of butane-1,4-diol was claimed to be about one million metric tons per year and market price is about US$2,000 (€1,600) per ton in 2005.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] In 2013, worldwide production was claimed to be billions of pounds (consistent with approximately one million metric tons).
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Almost half of it is dehydrated to tetrahydrofuran to make fibers such as Spandex.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is also used as a recreational drug known by some users as "Bute", "One Comma Four", "Liquid Fantasy", "One Four Bee" or "One Four B-D-O".
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Some federal courts in the United States have stated that 1,4-butanediol exerts effects similar to its metabolite, GABA analogue gamma-hydroxybutyrate (GHB), but several other federal courts have ruled that it does not.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] 1,4-but***e***nediol (CAS 110-64-5) may be incorrectly sold as 1,4-butanediol but should not be confused with it.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is rapidly converted into GHB acid by the enzymes alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase, and differing levels of these enzymes may account for differences in effects and side effects between users.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] While co-administration of ethanol and GHB already poses serious risks, co-administration of ethanol with 1,4-butanediol will interact considerably and has many other potential risks.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] This is because the same enzymes that are responsible for metabolizing alcohol also metabolize 1,4-butanediol so there is a strong chance of a dangerous drug interaction.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol seems to have two types of pharmacological actions.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] The major psychoactive effects of 1,4-butanediol are because it is metabolized into GHB; however there is a study suggesting that 1,4-butanediol may have potential alcohol-like pharmacological effects on its own.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] The study arrived at this conclusion based on the finding that butane-1,4-diol coadministered with ethanol led to potentiation of some of the behavioral effects of ethanol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] However, potentiation of ethanol's effects may simply be caused by competition for the alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase enzymes with co-administered 1,4-butanediol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] The shared metabolic rate-limiting steps thus leads to slowed metabolism and clearance for both compounds including ethanol's known toxic metabolite acetaldehyde.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Another study found no effect following intracerebroventricular injection of butane-1,4-diol in rats.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] This contradicts the hypothesis of butane-1,4-diol having inherent alcohol-like pharmacological effects.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Like gamma-hydroxybutyric acid, butane-1,4-diol is safe only in small amounts.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Adverse effects in higher doses include nausea, vomiting, dizziness, sedation, vertigo, and potentially death if ingested in large amounts.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Anxiolytic effects are diminished and side effects increased when used in combination with alcohol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] While butane-1,4-diol is not currently scheduled federally in the United States, a number of states have classified 1,4-butanediol as a controlled substance.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Individuals have been prosecuted for possession of 1,4-butanediol under the Federal Analog Act as substantially similar to GHB.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] A federal case in New York in 2002 ruled that 1,4-butanediol could not be considered an analog of GHB under federal law, but that decision was later overturned by the Second Circuit.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] A jury in Federal District Court in Chicago found that 1,4-butanediol was not an analog of GHB under federal law, which was not disputed on the case's appeal to the Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals, however this finding did not affect the outcome of the case.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] In the United Kingdom, 1,4-butanediol was scheduled in December 2009 (along with another GHB precursor, gamma-butyrolactone) as a Class C controlled substance.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] In Germany, the drug is not explicitly illegal, but might also be treated as illegal if used as a drug.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] It is controlled as a Schedule VI precursor in Canada.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] A toy called "Bindeez" ("Aqua Dots" in North America) was recalled by the distributor in November 2007 because of the presence of butane-1,4-diol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] The toy consists of small beads that stick to each other by sprinkling water.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] The production plant seems to have intended to cut costs by replacing less toxic pentane-1,5-diol with butane-1,4-diol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] ChemNet China listed the price of butane-1,4-diol at between about US$1,350–2,800 per metric ton, while the price for 1,5-pentanediol is about US$9,700 per metric ton.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] In August 2021, several people fell severely ill after consuming drinks at building L2.01 at the Lichtwiese Campus of Darmstadt Technical University, Germany.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Seven showed severe symptoms, two were transported to a hospital in Frankfurt am Main, and a 30-year-old person was, for a time, in a critical state.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol had been detected in milk packages, as well as in water filters.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] At the location, detectives also found bromophenols and dicyclohexylamine.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] A variety of 1,4-butanediol derivatives are GHB-like drugs or GHB receptor agonists.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] These include GHB itself, γ-butyrolactone (GBL), aceburic acid, ethyl acetoxy butanoate (EAB), Γ-crotonolactone, γ-hydroxybutyraldehyde, γ-hydroxyvaleric acid (GHV), γ-valerolactone (GVL), γ-hydroxycrotonic acid (GHC or T-HCA), and 4-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid (UMB68), among others.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-4-butanediol] An analogue that is not a 1,4-butanediol derivative but is related and still shows affinity for the GHB receptor is 3-chloropropanoic acid (UMB66).
[src:1-triacontanol/1-5-pentanediol] 1,5-Pentanediol is produced by hydrogenation of glutaric acid and its derivatives.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-5-pentanediol] It can also be prepared by hydrogenolysis of tetrahydrofurfuryl alcohol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-5-pentanediol] 1,4-Pentadiene can be prepared from 1,5-pentadiol via the diacetate.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-5-pentanediol] A toy called *Bindeez* (*Aqua Dots* in North America) was recalled by the distributor in November 2007 due to the unauthorized substitution of 1,5-pentanediol with 1,4-butanediol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-5-pentanediol] The toy consists of small beads that stick to each other when sprinkled with water.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-5-pentanediol] 1,4-Butanediol, which when ingested is metabolized to gamma-hydroxybutyric acid, was detected by GC-MS.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-5-pentanediol] ChemNet China lists the price of 1,4-butanediol at between US$1,350–2,800/tonne, while the price for 1,5-pentanediol is about US$9,700/tonne.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-aminoethanol] 1-Aminoethanol exists in a solution of acetaldehyde and aqueous ammonia.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-aminoethanol] 1-Aminoethanol is suggested as intermediate in Strecker reaction of alanine synthesis.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-aminoethanol] 1-Aminoethanol was first prepared in 1833 by the German chemist Johann Wolfgang Döbereiner; its empirical formula was first determined by the German chemist Justus von Liebig in 1835.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-aminoethanol] The structure of 1-aminoethanol remained unproven until 1877, when the German-Italian chemist Robert Schiff showed that the structure was CH3CH(OH)NH2.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] 1-Butanol occurs naturally as a minor product of the ethanol fermentation of sugars and other saccharides and is present in many foods and drinks.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] It is also a permitted artificial flavorant in the United States, used in butter, cream, fruit, rum, whiskey, ice cream and ices, candy, baked goods, and cordials.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] It is also used in a wide range of consumer products.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] The largest use of 1-butanol is as an industrial intermediate, particularly for the manufacture of butyl acetate (itself an artificial flavorant and industrial solvent).
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] It is a petrochemical derived from propylene.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Estimated production figures for 1997 are: United States 784,000 tonnes; Western Europe 575,000 tonnes; Japan 225,000 tonnes.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Since the 1950s, most 1-butanol is produced by the hydroformylation of propene (oxo process) to preferentially form the butyraldehyde n-butanal.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Typical catalysts are based on cobalt and rhodium.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Butyraldehyde is then hydrogenated to produce butanol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] In former times, butanol was prepared from crotonaldehyde, which can be obtained from acetaldehyde.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Butanol can also be produced by fermentation of biomass by bacteria.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Prior to the 1950s, *Clostridium acetobutylicum* was used in industrial fermentation to produce butanol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Research in the past few decades showed results of other microorganisms that can produce butanol through fermentation.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Butanol can be produced via furan hydrogenation over Pd or Pt catalyst at high temperature and high pressure.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Constituting 85% of its use, 1-butanol is mainly used in the production of varnishes.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] It is a popular solvent, e.g. for nitrocellulose.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] A variety of butanol derivatives are used as solvents, e.g. butoxyethanol or butyl acetate.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Many plasticizers are based on butyl esters, e.g., dibutyl phthalate.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] The monomer butyl acrylate is used to produce polymers.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] 1-Butanol has been proposed as a substitute for diesel fuel and gasoline.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] It is produced in small quantities in nearly all fermentations (see fusel oil).
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Clostridium produces much higher yields of butanol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Research is underway to increase the biobutanol yield from biomass.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Butanol is considered as a potential biofuel (butanol fuel).
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Butanol at 85 percent strength can be used in cars designed for gasoline without any change to the engine (unlike 85% ethanol), and it provides more energy for a given volume than ethanol, almost as much as gasoline.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Therefore, a vehicle using butanol would return fuel consumption more comparable to gasoline than ethanol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Butanol can also be added to diesel fuel to reduce soot emissions.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Butan-1-ol occurs naturally as a result of carbohydrate fermentation in a number of alcoholic beverages, including beer, grape brandies, wine, and whisky.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] It has been detected in the volatiles of hops, jack fruit, heat-treated milks, musk melon, cheese, southern pea seed, and cooked rice.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] 1-Butanol is also formed during deep frying of corn oil, cottonseed oil, trilinolein, and triolein.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Butan-1-ol is one of the "fusel alcohols" (from the German for "bad liquor"), which include alcohols that have more than two carbon atoms and have significant solubility in water.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] It is a natural component of many alcoholic beverages, albeit in low and variable concentrations.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] It (along with similar fusel alcohols) is reputed to be responsible for severe hangovers, although experiments in animal models show no evidence for this.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] The acute toxicity of 1-butanol is relatively low, with oral LD50 values of 790–4,360 mg/kg (rat; comparable values for ethanol are 7,000–15,000 mg/kg).
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] It is metabolized completely in vertebrates in a manner similar to ethanol: alcohol dehydrogenase converts 1-butanol to butyraldehyde; this is then converted to butyric acid by aldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Butyric acid can be fully metabolized to carbon dioxide and water by the β-oxidation pathway.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] In the rat, only 0.03% of an oral dose of 2,000 mg/kg was excreted in the urine.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] At sub-lethal doses, 1-butanol acts as a depressant of the central nervous system, similar to ethanol: one study in rats indicated that the intoxicating potency of 1-butanol is about 6 times higher than that of ethanol, possibly because of its slower transformation by alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Liquid 1-butanol, as is common with most organic solvents, is extremely irritating to the eyes; repeated contact with the skin can also cause irritation.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] This is believed to be a generic effect of defatting.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] No skin sensitization has been observed.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] Irritation of the respiratory pathways occurs only at very high concentrations (>2,400 ppm).
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] With a flash point of 35 °C, 1-butanol presents a moderate fire hazard: it is slightly more flammable than kerosene or diesel fuel but less flammable than many other common organic solvents.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-butanol] The depressant effect on the central nervous system (similar to ethanol intoxication) is a potential hazard when working with 1-butanol in enclosed spaces, although the odour threshold (0.2–30 ppm) is far below the concentration which would have any neurological effect.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-decanol] Decanol can be prepared by the hydrogenation of decanoic acid, which occurs in modest quantities in coconut oil (about 10%) and palm kernel oil (about 4%).
[src:1-triacontanol/1-decanol] It may also be produced synthetically via the Ziegler process.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-decanol] Decanol is used in the manufacture of plasticizers, lubricants, surfactants and solvents.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-decanol] Its ability to permeate the skin has led to it being investigated as a penetration enhancer for transdermal drug delivery.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-decanol] Like other medium chain fatty alcohols, 1-decanol is able to permeate the skin which can lead to irritation.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] In July 2000, docosanol was approved for medical use in the United States as an antiviral agent for reducing the duration of cold sores.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] It is an over-the-counter medication (OTC).
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] It is sold under the brand name **Abreva** among others.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] One of the most common side effects that has been reported from docosanol is headache.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] Headaches caused by the medication tend to be mild and can occur in any region of the head.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] In clinical trials, headache occurred in 10.4% of people treated with docosanol cream and 10.7% of people treated with placebo.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] The most serious side effects, although rare, are allergic reactions.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] Some of the patients experienced the symptoms of allergic reactions, including difficulty breathing, confusion, angioedema (facial swelling), fainting, dizziness, hives or chest pain.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] Other side effects may include: acne, burning, dryness, itching, rash, redness, acute diarrhea, soreness, swelling.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] Docosanol is thought to work by interfering with and stabilizing the host cell's surface phospholipids, preventing the fusion of the herpes virus's viral envelope with the human host cell.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] This disrupted ability of the virus to fuse with the host cell membrane prevents entry and subsequent replication.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] The drug was approved as a cream for oral herpes after clinical trials by the FDA in July 2000.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] It was shown to shorten the healing by 17.5 hours on average (95% confidence interval: 2 to 22 hours) in a placebo-controlled trial.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] Another trial showed no effect when treating the infected backs of guinea pigs.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-docosanol] Two experiments with 1-docosanol cream failed to show statistically significant differences by any parameter between 1-docosanol cream and vehicle control–treated sites or between 1-docosanol and untreated infection sites.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-dodecanol] In 1993, the European demand of dodecanol was around 60,000 tonnes per year.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-dodecanol] It can be obtained from palm kernel oil or coconut oil fatty acids and methyl esters by hydrogenation.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-dodecanol] A classic laboratory method involves Bouveault-Blanc reduction of ethyl laurate.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-dodecanol] Dodecanol is used to make surfactants, which are used in lubricating oils, and pharmaceuticals.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-dodecanol] It is also the precursor to dodecanal, an important fragrance, and 1-bromododecane, an alkylating agent for improving the lipophilicity of organic molecules.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-dodecanol] It has about half the toxicity of ethanol, but it is very harmful to marine organisms.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-dodecanol] The mutual solubility of 1-dodecanol and water has been quantified as follows.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Triacontanol was first isolated in 1933 from alfalfa wax.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] It was identified as a saturated straight chain primary alcohol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Triacontanol is found in various plant species as a minor component of the epicuticular wax.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] In wheat, triacontanol is about 3-4% of the leaf wax..
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] The effects of triacontanol may also be seen when a chopped alfafa plant is placed in close proximity to the seedlings and various crop seeds.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] A substantial increase in yield and growth has been seen in different plants, such as cucumber, tomatoes, wheat, maize, lettuce, and rice.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Triacontanol does not react the same way in all plant species.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] The effects of triacontanol various in terms of photosynthesis and the yield manipulation in plant species.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] The effects on C-3 plants and C-4 plants.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] In tomato plant (C-3 plant), the treatment of triacontanol increases the dry leaf weight and inhibited the photosynthesis by 27% in dry leaves,{{Eriksen AB, Selldén G, Skogen D, Nilsen S.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Comparative analyses of the effect of triacontanol on photosynthesis, photorespiration and growth of tomato (C3-plant) and maize (C 4-plant).
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] PMID: 24302317.|reason=photosynthesis does not occur in dry leaves|date=May 2020}} whereas in the maize plants no change in photosynthesis occurs whether treated by triacontanol or not.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Although, the basic effect of treating seedlings of various plant species is an increase in plant growth, photosynthesis and the yield of the crops, the effects of triacontanol are not the same in every plant species.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Some exhibit these symptoms while some show no response to the treatment to triacontanol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Different studies reveal that the effects of triacontanol differs with the amounts of the triacontanol used to treat the plant.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] A much higher dose of triacontanol could also have adverse effects on the growth of a plant.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Triacontanol has been reported to increase productivity of some plants that have some therapeutic properties.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] In addition, the effects of triacontanol are observed in opium and morphine production.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] There are numerous corporations making synthetic triacontanol for enhancing the crop yield and pest resistance in the crops.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Triacontanol improves the rate of cell division in a plant that produces larger roots and shoots.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] It has been shown that if triacontanol is applied during the maximized growth period of a plant in an appropriate amount, it enhances the enzymatic activity in the roots and hormone functionality increasing the overall performance of the plant.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Triacontanol basically operates by enhancing the basic functionality of the plant like increasing the rate of photosynthesis and producing more sugar such as glucose.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] When photosynthesis operates efficiently, the plant produce more sugars and absorb more sunlight.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] The plant then send more sugars to the rhizosphere via the root system where the growth, respiration and nutrient exchange take place in the vicinity of the soil.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] These microorganisms particularly trace the nutrients essential for the soil.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] These nutrients are further used by the plants to build more complex nutrients and compounds essential for rapid growth and defence from certain other microbes.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] These complex compounds maximize the yield of the crop.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Overall, despite other benefits from adequate amounts of triacontanol, the effect of enhanced photosynthesis may increase the plant outcomes.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] There are several chemical pathways via which triacontanol can be artificially synthesized.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] One method includes an organic compound succinic anhydride and a carboxylic acid docosanoic acid that have been used to attach the different carbon chains (C4 and C22) on 2 and 5 positions of thiophene, via two acylation sequences.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Later, 2-5 substituted thiophene is reacted for desulfurization using Raney Nickel.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] It produces triacontanoic acid which can be reduced with lithium aluminium hydride (LAH) to produce 1-triacontanol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Another method of synthesizing triacontanol focuses on the high yield with the easily available and feasible compounds that can form triacontanol through some chemical reactions in laboratory settings.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] 1-octadecanol or stearyl alcohol and 1,12-dodecanediol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Using the phase transfer system the 1-octadecanol is converted to octadecanal.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] On the other hand, 1,12-dodecanediol goes through the phase transfer bromination and further reacted with 1-hydroxy-12-triphenylphosphonium bromide.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Both the end products of the two compounds undergo Witting reaction to give the product.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] The resulted mixture is hydrogenated to give triacontanol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Cocoa seedlings (*Theobroma cacao* L.) shows a positive growth in terms of plant length and the leaf size when treated with triacontanol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Treating the cocoa plant with excess amount of triacontanol led to inhibition of plant growth and bearing of adverse effects on the plant physiology.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] The provision of triacontanol rapidly increase the morphogenetic response in the plant during the embryogenesis process.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] The enhanced response lead to increase in the cell division and cell growth by the growth regulators.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Moreover, it also leads to increased shoots and roots of the plant.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] The whole process results from the formation of new growth and development proteins and new mRNA.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] In the hypocotyl treatment of triacontanol in the mangrove plant resulted in increased root and shoot growth.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] The rise in the number of primary and secondary roots, the length of roots, height and the biomass resulted from triacontanol treatment.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Moreover, the reduction of nitrate reductase as well as increase amount of chlorophylls in the photosystem 1 and 2 observed.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] However, the increase in the concentration of triacontanol resulted in the decrease of the plant growth. hence, the amount of the alcohol treatment is the driving force for the enhanced results.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Triacontanol also increases the growth of a cell *in vitro* by increasing the cell number in the culture.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] It can be attributed to the increase protein formation and rapid cell division induced by triacontanol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] The growth of cell culture *in vitro* has been done with various plant species to observe the effects of triacontanol.
[src:1-triacontanol/1-triacontanol] Similar effects of triacontanol can be seen with a variety of plants like rice, wheat, maize, cucumber, and many more.
